# openrouter-kimi-sonnet-mono-router overlay — OpenRouter Kimi K3 + Sonnet

Read this when launched with `openrouter-kimi-sonnet-mono-router`. You are the
one resident Claude Code process, billed through **OpenRouter**
(`OPENROUTER_API_KEY` + `ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=https://openrouter.ai/api`). Each
stage respawns onto a model tailored to that role.

## Model routing (this pack)

| Role | OpenRouter model | Why |
|------|------------------|-----|
| coder | `moonshotai/kimi-k3` | Long-horizon implementation, repo navigation, debugging |
| architect | `moonshotai/kimi-k3` | Deep code reasoning across modules and boundaries |
| hardender | `moonshotai/kimi-k3` | Mutation/coverage work is code-heavy |
| specifier | `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6` | Crisp structured specs and acceptance criteria |
| cleaner / documenter | `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6` | Mechanical refactor and docs |
| QA | `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6` | Verification gate — run suites, bounce with evidence |
| coordinator | `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6` | Bookkeeping — promote, route, close (separate process) |

## Pipeline shape

Same as `swarmforge/PIPELINE.md` / mono-router: **coder (home) → cleaner →
architect → hardender → documenter → QA**. Coordinator is a separate process.

## How you rotate

After `swarm_handoff.sh <draft>` (or terminal QA action):

1. Note the `to:` role.
2. Run **`rotate_to_role.sh <that-role>`** — respawns this pane as that role
   (new model + prompt).
3. On wake, `RESUME-ON-START` → `ready_for_next.sh` first.

## Non-home roles: rotate home after any note, including merge-up (BL-550)

QA's merge-up note broadcasts to all 5 pipeline roles at once. On the full
7-pack each role is its own process and idles independently; on this pack
there is ONE resident, and it strands in whichever non-home role processed
the LAST merge-up note unless it rotates itself back out.

As a **non-home role** (cleaner, architect, hardender, documenter), after
`done_with_current.sh` completes any note — including a merge-up note — if
your inbox is then empty, call `rotate_to_role.sh coder` yourself. Do not
wait for a coordinator chase.

`ready_for_next.sh` also codes this at the tool level as a backstop: as a
non-home role with an empty mailbox it prints `ROTATE_HOME` (never
`NO_TASK`) and rotates you to the home role on its own. Treat that as a
safety net, not a substitute — rotate proactively after a note rather than
relying on the next `ready_for_next.sh` call to catch it.

## After a parcel finishes (QA done) — home vs intake drain

When the parcel ends (QA approved; coordinator does bookkeeping — you do not
merge), do **not** always rotate straight home to coder.

1. **Scan the backlog root** (`backlog/*.yaml` and `backlog/*.yml` sitting
   directly under `backlog/`, not in `active/`/`paused/`/`done/`). Those are
   raw human intakes.
2. If **any root intake exists**, rotate to specifier and drain them first:
   `rotate_to_role.sh specifier`
   On wake as specifier: run `ready_for_next.sh` if a parcel is waiting; else
   drain the root per constitution / specifier.prompt (write proper specs into
   `backlog/paused/`, remove the raw root files, note the coordinator). Root
   intake beats promoting or picking up already-paused work.
3. If the root is **empty**, rotate **home**: `rotate_to_role.sh coder`.
   The coordinator — woken by QA's close/bookkeeping handoff — must in the
   **same turn**: Close → Promote next eligible paused → **Route Work to coder**
   (see coordinator.prompt QA bookkeeping step 3 /
   `promote_and_route_next.sh` / `route_backlog_to_coder.sh`).
   There is **no** coordinator self-loop; if you land as coder and get
   `NO_TASK` with an open slot and paused work, send **one** note asking the
   coordinator to promote+route, then idle for wake. Then run
   `ready_for_next.sh` for the Work parcel.

## Idle at home (coder) with no parcel

If you are **coder**, `ready_for_next.sh` returns `NO_TASK`, and the backlog
root still has intake files — do not stay conversationally idle. Rotate to
specifier and drain (`rotate_to_role.sh specifier`). Specifier is not only for
downstream spec bounces; on this pack it also owns cold root-intake drain when
the pipeline is otherwise empty.

## Handoff drafts

Write to `swarmforge/runtime/handoff-draft.txt`, then
`swarmforge/scripts/swarm_handoff.sh` on that file. Never repo-root `tmp/`.

## Idle at home — STOP after NO_TASK (mono-router anti-loop)

When you are the home resident (**coder**) and `ready_for_next.sh` returns
`NO_TASK`:

1. **Do not re-run** `ready_for_next.sh` / do not self-poll / do not invent a
   `/loop`. Exit the turn and wait for a tmux/operator/daemon wake.
2. If backlog **root** still has `backlog/*.yaml` intakes → `rotate_to_role.sh specifier`.
3. Else if `backlog/active/` is empty (or under cap with an open slot) and
   `backlog/paused/` has eligible work → send **one** `note` to coordinator
   (`swarm_handoff.sh`) asking it to **promote + route** the next eligible
   paused ticket to coder, then idle for wake.
4. Coordinator: same anti-loop. On a QA-close wake or this note, with open
   capacity under `active_backlog_max_depth`, Close (if needed) → Promote →
   Route Work to coder in one turn — do not wait for a human chat.
5. If you ignore (1) and keep re-polling, the **handoff daemon will hard-stop
   the entire swarm** (endless-loop circuit breaker) to stop token burn.
